After learning Neovim and Git commands, what companies usually expect is workflow, not memorizing commands.

1. Start your day
git pull

Get the latest changes from the team.

Open project:

nvim .
2. Find the task

Maybe:

Fix bug
Add feature
Refactor code

Read the code using:

gg
G
/search
w b e

Navigate quickly until you understand the code.

3. Create a branch

Never work directly on main.

git switch -c fix-login-bug

or

git switch -c add-user-validation
4. Edit code

Use:

ciw
dd
yy
p
u

and save:

:w

Repeat until feature/bug is done.

5. Check changes
git diff

Review what you changed.

6. Stage files
git add .

or

git add file.c
7. Commit
git commit -m "Fix login validation bug"

Good commit message:

Add user authentication
Fix memory leak
Refactor parser
Improve error handling
8. Push branch
git push -u origin fix-login-bug
9. Create Pull Request

GitHub UI or:

gh pr create

Team reviews your code.

10. If review asks for changes

Edit code:

nvim file.c

Commit again:

git add .
git commit -m "Address review comments"
git push
11. After PR merged

Switch back:

git switch main

Get latest:

git pull

Delete old branch:

git branch -d fix-login-bug
Daily workflow (the one you'll repeat 1000 times)
git pull

git switch -c feature-name

nvim .

(edit code)

git diff

git add .

git commit -m "message"

git push

Create PR

Review

Merge

git pull
